p>Now consider the treatment effect when instead of minimizing the Euclidean distance, I minimized the Maha distance.  Yes, the treatment effect changed, but that’s not a surprise as it’s a different pairing.  It did not give equal weight to the covariates’ discrepancies, and as a result, it had a somewhat different pairing. I care about showing you something else.  This one used several units multiple times for the matching.  And so go back to columns 3 and 4 in my table. Same syntax as before but here I get different standard errors. Can you guess why? Look below to see for yourself. </p><p>Matching with replacement reduces the bias, but it increases the variance, as we see in the formula above.  And to see exactly what happened, let’s go back to our <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1iro1Qzrr1eLDY_LJVzOYvnQZWmxY8JyTcDf6YcdhkwQ/edit?usp=sharing" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">google spreadsheet</a> (click on the Maha tab). But I made color coded pictures for us now, too. </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Faf47deac-560f-42a4-be5c-4c3239d0e0ab_924x1502.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Iu4w9eWqHLzYd1B1HwRM5K_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ee3Sgh6E_YxOAHUB2xFY4onEGo_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rR6hQkmHvENvQ9LDwKqVVSm9UVaSP9-66rK5xdYf1uI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGYWY0N2RlYWMtNTYwZi00MmE0LWJlNWMtNGMzMjM5ZDBlMGFiXzkyNHgxNTAyLnBuZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mzVLhxjRqtMvBW86NbmgKBZE5d_" al